{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":13673,"name":"","username":"rku","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/rku/{size}/3200_2.png","created_at":"2016-09-20T11:16:31.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003ePicture worth a thousand words: \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t5uI_6JEswM\u0026amp;feature=youtu.be\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003eyoutube.com/watch?v=t5uI_6J ‚Ä¶ e=youtu.be\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\nNotice that micro-shaking when object moves. This apparently is because object is flat-shaded. Is there any way to make it look smooth while keeping flat shading? If i set faces of object to be smooth-shaded then movement is also silky smooth, however shading effect is gone.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:14:17.465Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":16,"reads":6,"readers_count":5,"score":83.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":2254,"topic_slug":"flat-shaded-object-movement-is-jittery","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t5uI_6JEswM\u0026feature=youtu.be","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"YouTube","clicks":7}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":246,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":13675,"name":"Lasse √ñ√∂rni","username":"cadaver","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/cadaver/{size}/3_2.png","created_at":"2016-09-20T11:58:14.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIt‚Äôs caused by triangle rasterization. Without antialiasing triangles have to fall on whole pixels, which may lead to 1-pixel jitter of their size when they move.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf the shading effect was a texture instead of geometry, then it would be interpolated/filtered across the object face and would appear less jittery.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:14:17.591Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":6,"readers_count":5,"score":1.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":2254,"topic_slug":"flat-shaded-object-movement-is-jittery","display_username":"Lasse √ñ√∂rni","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Urho3D Author","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":true,"staff":true,"user_id":3,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":13676,"name":"","username":"rku","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/rku/{size}/3200_2.png","created_at":"2016-09-20T15:45:04.000Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote\"\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eshading effect was a texture instead of geometry\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat does this mean exactly? If you mean baking effect into texture then it is not ideal as it would not take into account lighting when rotating.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:14:17.661Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":6,"readers_count":5,"score":1.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":2254,"topic_slug":"flat-shaded-object-movement-is-jittery","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":246,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":13686,"name":"Lasse √ñ√∂rni","username":"cadaver","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/cadaver/{size}/3_2.png","created_at":"2016-09-21T08:03:59.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eYes, I mean baking.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor other solutions, you could try if antialiasing helps. Or determining the world unit distance of one pixel, and snapping all object positioning to that, so that you don‚Äôt get sub-pixel rasterization artifacts. Otherwise than that, you can‚Äôt really change how rasterization happens.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:14:18.432Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":6,"readers_count":5,"score":1.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":2254,"topic_slug":"flat-shaded-object-movement-is-jittery","display_username":"Lasse √ñ√∂rni","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Urho3D Author","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":true,"staff":true,"user_id":3,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":13757,"name":"","username":"rku","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/rku/{size}/3200_2.png","created_at":"2016-09-23T15:06:05.000Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThank you cadaver, snapping movement to pixel did the trick.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor the poor souls reading this in the future this is what i did:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFirst i set up orthographic camera size properly:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e_pixels_per_unit = round((float)graphics.GetHeight() / PLAY_FIELD_HEIGHT_UNITS);\ncamera_object-\u0026gt;SetOrthoSize(graphics.GetHeight() / _pixels_per_unit);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd then setting position of object x y and z have to be snapped to pixels using this:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003e\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-01-02T01:14:23.329Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":5,"readers_count":4,"score":1.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":2254,"topic_slug":"flat-shaded-object-movement-is-jittery","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":246,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false}],"stream":[13673,13675,13676,13686,13757]},"timeline_lookup":[[1,2255],[4,2254],[5,2252]],"suggested_topics":[{"id":7132,"title":"How to Draw Anti-Aliased Outlined Line on the UI layer?","fancy_title":"How to Draw Anti-Aliased Outlined Line on the UI layer?","slug":"how-to-draw-anti-aliased-outlined-line-on-the-ui-layer","posts_count":8,"reply_count":5,"highest_post_number":8,"image_url":"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/up